You examines qualitative shifts in health and healing spurred by these reforms, and analyzes the dilemmas they create for health professionals and patients alike. It also explores how cultural frameworks, particularly those stemming from Islam and Wolof ethnomedicine, are central to understanding how people manage vulnerability to ill health. While offering a critique of neoliberal health policies, Your Pocket Is What Cures You remains grounded in ethnography to highlight the struggles of men and women who are precariously balanced on twin precipices of crumbling health systems and economic decline. Their stories demonstrate what happens when market-based health reforms collide with material, political, and social realities in African societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMedical anthropologyxSenegalxSaint-Louis Region. 0aMedical anthropologyzSenegalzSaint-Louis (Region). 0aMedical anthropologyzSenegalzSaint-Louis Region. 0aMedical carexSenegalxSaint-Louis Region. 0aMedical carezSenegalzSaint-Louis (Region). 0aMedical carezSenegalzSaint-Louis Region. 0aMedical economicsxSenegalxSaint-Louis Region. 0aMedical economicszSenegalzSaint-Louis (Region). 0aMedical economicszSenegalzSaint-Louis Region. 0aMedical policyxSenegalxSaint-Louis Region. 0aMedical policyzSenegalzSaint-Louis (Region). 0aMedical policyzSenegalzSaint-Louis Region. 0aPublic healthxSenegalxSaint-Louis Region. 0aPublic healthzSenegalzSaint-Louis (Region). 0aPublic healthzSenegalzSaint-Louis Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354907140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813549071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9